li.p:
We need: numerator degree greater than denominator degree (no horizontal asymptote); zeros at x=-5 and x=3; single vertical asymptote at x=-1; and the correct end behavior.  The function

  s(x) = -\frac{(x+5)(x-3)}{x+1}

satisfies all criteria: as x \to \infty, s(x) \to -\infty (since -(+)(+)/(+) \to -\infty); as x \to -\infty, s(x) \to +\infty.
